<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRAZIL URGES BROADER U.N. SECURITY COUNCIL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BRASILIA, Brazil 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Fernando Collor de Mello has proposed doubling the number of 
permanent members of the U.N. Security Council, admitting Japan, Germany, 
India, Brazil and an unspecified African country. 
</P>
<P>
Television and newspaper reports said the Brazilian president made the 
suggestion in brief talks in Tokyo on Sunday with Japanese Prime Minister 
Toshiki Kaifu. 
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian idea is that the five suggested new members would not have a 
veto. The existing permanent members, the United States, Soviet Union, China, 
Britain and France, all have veto power. 
</P>
<P>
Total membership of the Security Council is currently 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
