<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: ART 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CLAUDIA PUIG , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Garbo's Things Not Alone: For a limited time only, thousands of New Yorkers are 
walking on Greta Garbo's rugs, eyeballing her Renoirs and inspecting items that 
are expected to fetch $20 million when auctioned off this week by Sotheby's. 
Garbo's paintings go on sale today and Wednesday, and her furniture, including 
a Louis XV chair with a rip in its salmon upholstery, is to be sold Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
The Garbo collection will remain on view at the auction house next to the Henry 
Ford II collection of Impressionist paintings, department store king Jerome 
Ohrbach's collection of Monets and Matisses and paintings that belonged to the 
late violinist Jascha Heifetz. More than 7,000 visitors have viewed the Garbo 
exhibit since its opening Friday. CLAUDIA PUIG 
</P>
</TEXT>
