<HEADLINE>
<P>
KEATING GRAND JURY CONSIDERED OTHER S&amp;L INDICTMENTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JAMES S. GRANELLI, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The state grand jury that indicted Charles H. Keating Jr. and three others on 
securities fraud also considered charging several other employees of Lincoln 
Savings &amp; Loan and its parent firm with wrongdoing, recently released grand 
jury transcripts reveal. 
</P>
<P>
But to keep the complex case manageable, prosecutors advised the 22-member 
panel to limit the indictment to the top officials of Lincoln and Phoenix-based 
American Continental Corp. 
</P>
<P>
"We want to go after the people truly responsible for this behavior in a way 
that promises some possibility of success in a time frame soon enough to be 
meaningful to the victims," Los Angeles County Deputy Dist. Atty. Thomas 
Papageorge told the grand jurors. 
</P>
<P>
The result was a 42-count indictment in mid-September for alleged securities 
fraud against Keating, former American Continental President Judy J. Wischer 
and Robin S. Symes and Ray C. Fidel, both former presidents of Irvine-based 
Lincoln. 
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Los Angeles Superior Court Judge Lance A. Ito set aside 22 counts of 
the indictment because many of the charges did not clearly state the alleged 
wrongdoing. The judge gave the prosecutors until Nov. 19 to rewrite the 
indictment. 
</P>
<P>
The indictment charges the defendants with falsely stating and failing to state 
the true risks associated with the sale of $200 million in American Continental 
bonds to more than 17,000 investors. Those bonds became worthless after the 
company filed for bankruptcy protection in April, 1989, and regulators seized 
Lincoln the next day. Regulators estimate that Lincoln's collapse will cost 
taxpayers more than $2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
The grand jury transcripts, which were released Friday, give a picture of the 
prosecutor's strategy. The state wanted to keep the indictment narrow to make 
it understandable to a trial court jury. 
</P>
<P>
Toward that end, prosecutors decided to drop their original effort to seek 
charges of conspiracy and grand theft by false pretenses because the charges 
were too complex and difficult to prove, the grand jury transcripts show. 
</P>
<P>
At the closing arguments before the grand jury on Sept. 11, prosecutors came 
with a proposed indictment in hand naming Keating and three others. They argued 
against expanding the case to include more defendants or more charges. 
</P>
<P>
One of the grand jurors, Glenn Buchanan of Sherman Oaks, confirmed in an 
interview Monday that the panel considered including several other Lincoln and 
American Continental officials in the indictment but finally agreed with the 
prosecutor's approach. 
</P>
<P>
Buchanan said grand jurors considered bringing charges against American 
Continental executives Robert J. Kielty, Andrew Ligget and Jack D. Atchison and 
Lincoln executive Dariush Razavi, a top aide to Fidel. The grand jury discussed 
indicting at least two others. 
</P>
<P>
While none of the people identified by Buchanan have been indicted, their names 
appear often in the 4,500 pages of grand jury testimony publicly released. They 
could not be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
Before joining American Continental at a salary of nearly $1 million, Atchison 
had been a partner at the accounting firm of Arthur Young &amp; Co. in Phoenix 
and was head of the audit team that produced the last two American Continental 
financial statements. 
</P>
<P>
Those statements, much criticized by thrift regulators, were largely what the 
state Department of Corporations relied on in approving the sale of American 
Continental bonds, even though the state agency's staff had developed a strong 
case for denying approval of the bond sale. 
</P>
<P>
The grand jury also wanted to delve more into the role of state regulators in 
the sale of nearly $200 million worth of debt securities at Irvine-based 
Lincoln's 29 Southern California branches, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Buchanan said a minority of grand jurors wanted to bring in more regulators to 
determine the state's role in approving the sale of the bonds, but proposals to 
subpoena them were defeated. A separate investigation by the Sacramento 
district attorney's office is looking into possible wrongdoing involving state 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
The grand jury also narrowly voted down a proposal to subpoena U.S. Sen. Alan 
Cranston (D-Calif.), he said, to testify about his relationship with Keating, 
former chairman of American Continental. 
</P>
<P>
In August, near the end of the investigation, the grand jury came close to 
issuing a subpoena for Cranston, Buchanan said, but instead sent a letter 
simply requesting him to appear. The senator's lawyer responded at the time 
that Cranston, who was out of the country at the time, was too busy and could 
not provide meaningful information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Charles H. Keating Jr. Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
